\i Suit was originally filed under order 33 of the CPR as a summary suit on a specially endorsed plaint. The defendant on the 29\super th\nosupersub  September 2004 was granted leave to file a defence- Company-Limited liability-lifting the veil- Section 58 of the Evidence Act.\

\b \ul Brief facts:\

\b0 \ulnone The plaintiff entered a Memorandum of Understanding (MOU) with the defendants trading as Children\'92s Vision Uganda (CVU) to provide a financial subsidy for orphaned children studying at Masajja Modern Primary School.
\f1\i0 \uc0\u8232 
\f0\i According to the Memorandum of Understanding it was agreed that the defendant would send students to the plaintiff\'92s school and pay as a school fees a subsidy (being 50% of the school fees) of Ug.Shs.25,000/= for each day attending student and Ug.Shs.65,00/= for each boarder. The plaintiff then admitted the said students into the school and taught and fed them. The implementation of the Memorandum of Understanding started well as the first term fees (subsidiary) was paid in full. However, the second term fees were not paid leaving a balance of Ug.Shs.12,350,000/=. Despite various demands the defendants have not paid the money. Apart from attending the application for leave to defend and filing a defence the defendant\'92s lawyers did not attend the main trial despite the service on them of the hearing notice several times.\

\b \ul Issues:\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl420\ql\qnatural\pardirnatural

\b0 \cf0 \ulnone Whether the defendant is liable without the company Children Vision Uganda being sued-\
If the defendant is liable whether he is to pay the whole sum claimed as prayed.-Remedies.\

\f2\i0\b \

\f0\i \ul Held:\

\b0 \ulnone The defendant was liable without Children Vision Uganda being sued.
